  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do I always feel a headache?",
  "response": "Headaches can be caused by a variety of factors, and it's important to identify the specific cause to find the right treatment. Here are some common reasons for recurring headaches:\n\n1. **Tension Headaches**: Often caused by stress, anxiety, or muscle strain. These are the most common type of headache and can feel like a tight band around your head.\n\n2. **Migraines**: These can be more severe and are often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light or sound. Migraines can have genetic causes and may be triggered by certain foods, hormonal changes, or environmental factors.\n\n3. **Cluster Headaches**: These are less common but very painful. They tend to occur in clusters and are more common in men than women.\n\n4. **Sinus Headaches**: Caused by inflammation in your sinuses, often due to infection or allergies.\n\n5. **Dehydration**: Not drinking enough water can lead to headaches.\n\n6. **Caffeine Withdrawal**: If you regularly consume caffeine and suddenly stop, you may experience withdrawal headaches.\n\n7. **Sleep Issues**: Both too much and too little sleep can trigger headaches.\n\n8. **Eye Strain**: Long hours in front of a screen or reading without breaks can cause headaches.\n\n9. **Diet**: Certain foods and beverages, like those containing monosodium glutamate (MSG), nitrates, or alcohol, can trigger headaches.\n\n10. **Medication Overuse**: Overuse of pain relievers can lead to rebound headaches.\n\nIf your headaches are frequent or severe, it's important to consult a healthcare professional. They can help diagnose the cause and suggest appropriate treatment. In the meantime, keeping a headache diary can help you and your doctor identify patterns and potential triggers.",
